n image;\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\nI think this should work since `makePowerOfTwo()` is only used inside `uploadTexture()`. When the generated image data are uploaded to the GPU memory via `texImage2D()`, there should be no problem to overwrite the canvas with other data. A new upload should also be no problem since this triggers the recreation of the POT image data.\r\n\r\nAlso see https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/11378#issuecomment-303490621","created_at":"2018-01-26T20:15:08.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12469#issuecomment-360892944","id":360892944,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12469","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM2MDg5Mjk0NA==","updated_at":"2018-01-29T11:57:11.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/360892944","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/12612165?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/Mugen87","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyNjEyMTY1","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"Mugen87","type":"User","id":12612165,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/Mugen87\/orgs"}},{"index":15,"author_association":"NONE","body":"@Mugen87  In the webgl_test_memory example the images are created using a canvas like so: \r\n\r\n> function createImage() {\r\n> \t\t\t\tvar canvas = document.createElement( 'canvas' );\r\n> \t\t\t\tcanvas.width = 1000; \/\/initial 256\r\n> \t\t\t\tcanvas.height = 1000; \/\/initial 256\r\n> ....\r\n> \t\t\t\treturn canvas;\r\n> \t\t\t} \r\n\r\nAs I mentioned, with the canvas size changed from 256x256 to 1000x1000 in this example will result in GPU memory greater that 3GB in Firefox in couple of seconds ...and crash. \r\nIn this example I have tried to reuse the same canvas (not the canvas in Three.js makePowerOfTwo code)  and it seems to work better.\r\n\r\nSo, I tried the solution\/change you mentioned in the Three.js code, same example with 1000x1000 dimensions, same problem, memory goes beyond 3GB fast.\r\nI tried a small change that has managed to maintain acceptable amount of GPU memory and avoid crash, I commented this warning : \r\n\r\n> console.warn( 'THREE.WebGLRenderer: image is not power of two...\r\n\r\n","created_at":"2018-01-29T10:05:27.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12469#issuecomment-361197033","id":361197033,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/12469","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM2MTE5NzAzMw==","updated_at":"2018-01-29T10:05:27.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/361197033","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars1.githubusercontent.com\/u\/35533014?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/alinhulea","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjM1NTMzMDE0","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alinhulea\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","s